Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=731595" target="_blank">Prothit</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            Purely on the stats that Mr. Tharoor has provided:<br/><br/>
Total murders (1980, 1990, 2000, 2010) = 22149, 35045, 37399, 33335<br/>
India population in billions (1980, 1990, 2000, 2010) = 0.699 0.8689, 1.042, 1.206<br/><br/>
Therefore, # murders per billion people (1980, 1990, 2000, 2010) = 31686, 40332, 35891, 27641<br/><br/>
Let's relate the capital punishment causality to these per capita numbers. Given there was a spike in per capita murders between 1980 and 1990, it is logical that there had to be 10 hangings. It potentially acted as a deterrent for the next decade (1990 to 2000) whereby the per capita murders actually reduced by 11%. The effectiveness of the deterrence tool (i.e. capital punishment) has been such that in the next decade (2000 to 2010), not only the per capita number, but the absolute number of murders has itself declined- which is remarkable! Still no correlation, Mr. Tharoor?<br/><br/>
For something to be a deterrent, the dependent variable associated with it (in this case, murder), needs to be seen after a lag, which I show above. Also, absolute numbers of murders make no sense in a growing population. So your metric itself was not meaningful.
                         </div>



