Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=729971" target="_blank">AK</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            That punishment is not a deterrent for a crime is logically applicable to the capital penalty, then it should also be applicable to other forms of punishment including life imprisonment. As you have said, there is no guarantee of a convict being given the death penalty even if he has committed murder. Similarly, there is no guarantee of a convict being imprisoned for life even if he has committed a serious offence. All that lies in the strength of the prosecution, the quality of legal representation and judge's interpretation of the arguments; all of which are variables over which the state has little or no control, and this is true around the world. So, going by this logic, even life imprisonment is not a worthy punishment because it incarcerates a person for life without ever having served as a deterrent to him or anybody else. SO, why do we need harsh punishments at all? The purpose is to reform the individual, which is obviously hardly served in such cases! That again brings the question of which is the more cruel form of punishment, life imprisonment or death? That is a subjective question, which only a convict on death row can answer. The only reason a death penalty can be offered is when it looks inevitable; i.e. when there seems to be no reasonable hope of the individual being able to reform himself and resume a normal life in society, either because he seems to be an obsessive criminal or because the grave nature of his crime is such that the society is unlikely to accept him back. Exile is perhaps the only other option.
                         </div>



